result.execSummary:
The defendant Cheyenne M Simpson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft - County Ordinance. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Cash bail applied to fine of $859.50. Sentence credit of 13 days was granted in lieu of payment of balance. Fine considered paid in full.

District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  State amends the charge to a County Ordinance, Theft, 13-102(c)(12).  Attorney Martinez enters a plea of no contest to the County Ordinance charge of Theft.  State makes sentencing recommendations.  Defense makes sentencing recommendations.  Court sentences the defendant as follows:

Count 1:
FINE:  $859.50
Cash bail in the amount of $250.00 to be applied.
Balance due is $609.50.
The alternate sentence is 13 days jail.  Credit time 13-days jail.
Court considers time served and there is no balance due.
